'''SS ''Empire Tower''''' was a British {{GRT|4378}} [[cargo ship]] built in 1935 and sunk by enemy action in 1943.
She was built by the [[Burntisland Shipbuilding Company]] Ltd. in [[Fife]], Scotland. The North Eastern Marine Engineering Co. Ltd. of [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]] built her 335 [[Horsepower#Nominal horsepower|NHP]] three-cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engine]].<ref name=LR/> She had six corrugated furnaces with a combined heating surface of {{convert|117|sqft|0}} heat to heat her three 180 [[Pounds per square inch|lb<sub>f</sub>/in<sup>2</sup>]] single-ended boilers, which had a combined heating surface of {{convert|5445|sqft|0}}.<ref name=LR/> She was fitted with [[direction finding]] equipment.<ref name=LR/>
She was launched as '''SS ''Roxburgh''''' for [[Arthur Sutherland|B.J. Sutherland and Company]] of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]].<ref name=WreckSite/> In 1937 the Tower Hill Steamship Company, an offshoot of [[Counties Ship Management]], bought her and renamed her '''SS ''Tower Field'''''.<ref name=WreckSite/>
==Damage and repair== On 10 May 1941 ''Tower Field'' was steaming in ballast from London to Newcastle when a German aircraft attacked and damaged her off the Outer Dowsing Buoy in the [[Thames Estuary]].<ref name=U2717/> She was repaired and returned to service.<ref name=U2717/>
On 19 October 1941 she was entering [[Workington]] Channel off [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] with a cargo of iron ore when she ran aground and fractured her hull.<ref name=U2717/> She broke in two but her cargo was discharged and she was refloated and repaired.<ref name=U2717/>
The [[Ministry of War Transport]] took her over and renamed her '''SS ''Empire Tower''''' but kept her under CSM management.<ref name=LR/> She returned to service in December 1942.<ref name=U2717/>
{{location map|North Atlantic|width=304 |lat= 43.50 |long= -14.46 |caption=Approximate position of ''Empire Tower''{{'}}s wreck |relief= yes }}
==Sinking== Early in 1943 ''Empire Tower'', under Captain David John Williams OBE, joined [[List of convoy codes#X|Convoy XK-2]] from [[Gibraltar]] to the UK.<ref name=U2717/> On 5 March the [[German Type IX submarine]]<ref name=U130>{{cite web |url= http://www.uboat.net/boats/u130.htm |title=U-130 |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |date=1995–2010 |work=uboat.net |publisher=Guðmundur Helgason |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> {{GS|U-130|1941|2}} attacked the convoy and sank ''Empire Tower'', {{SS|Fidra||2}}, {{SS|Ger-y-Bryn||2}} and {{SS|Trefusis||2}}.<ref name=U2717/><ref>{{cite book |last=Slader |first=John |title=The Red Duster at War |year=1988 |publisher=William Kimber & Co Ltd |location=London |isbn=0-7183-0679-1 |page=253}} </ref> ''Empire Tower'' sank within a minute and Captain Williams, six gunners and 35 crew were lost.<ref name=U2717/> The [[Royal Navy]] [[naval trawler|armed trawler]] {{HMS|Loch Oskaig|FY 175|6}} rescued three survivors and landed them at [[Derry|Londonderry]],<ref name=U2717/> [[Northern Ireland]].
One week later, on 12 March, a [[depth charge]] attack by [[United States Navy|US Navy]] destroyer {{USS|Champlin|DD-601|6}} west of the [[Azores]] sank ''U-130'' with the loss of all 53 hands.<ref name=U130/>
